          "body": "The Judah oracle is the chapter's theological center of gravity and one of the most important messianic texts in the entire Old Testament. Jacob piles up images of conquest, royalty, and unchallenged sovereignty: Judah's brothers bow to him (49:8), his hand is on the neck of his enemies (49:8), he is a lion no one dares rouse (49:9). Then the oracle peaks at verse 10: 'The scepter shall not depart from Judah, nor the ruler's staff from between his feet, until Shiloh comes, and to him shall be the obedience of the peoples.' The scepter and ruler's staff are the twin emblems of royal governance. Their continuous presence in Judah — 'shall not depart' — anticipates the Davidic monarchy. But the oracle does not end with David. It points past David to a figure whose arrival is the goal of Judah's entire kingly history. The term 'Shiloh' has generated centuries of debate: (1) a place-name (contextually unlikely); (2) a relative clause sheloh, 'until he comes to whom it belongs' (Ezekiel 21:27 uses the same construction); (3) a royal title meaning 'the peaceful one.' All three readings converge on the same referent: a coming individual to whom universal allegiance belongs. The New Testament's identification of Jesus as the Lion of the tribe of Judah (Rev. 5:5) and the Root of David is the canonical reading of this text. The imagery of verses 11-12 — garments washed in wine, teeth white from milk — depicts the agricultural abundance of a kingdom so rich that wine is as common as water. The Revelator's image of Christ with a robe dipped in blood (Rev. 19:13) may echo this oracle's 'robes in the blood of grapes.'"
