          "title": "Eight brief oracles — character, geography, and destiny",
          "body": "The eight shorter oracles (Zebulun through Benjamin, vv. 13-27) operate at a lower theological register than Judah's but are rich with image. Zebulun gets a coastal vocation (49:13). Issachar, the strong donkey lying between the sheepfolds, chooses comfort over freedom and ends in servitude (49:14-15) — a warning about the long-term cost of pragmatic comfort. Dan's snake imagery (49:16-17) depicts a tribe that fights by ambush, effective but morally ambiguous — the tribe that later establishes unauthorized worship at Dan (Judges 18). The interjection at verse 18 — 'For Your salvation I wait, O LORD' — is the chapter's pastoral hinge: Jacob, after depicting Dan's serpentine cunning, drops the poetic frame and cries out personally to Yahweh for yeshuah (salvation). Gad will be raided but will raid back (49:19). Asher will produce royal food (49:20). Naphtali is a doe let loose who gives beautiful words (49:21). Benjamin is a ravenous wolf who devours prey — a portrait fulfilled in the tribe's fierce military history (Judg. 20–21) and in Saul of Tarsus, who described his pre-conversion self with exactly Benjamin's wolf-vocabulary (Phil. 3:5-6)."
